he frenzy of activity slows, the internationals go home, local groups disappear from sight, and the NGO boom goes bust. Instead of peace and stability, the embrace of NGOs and the enthusiasm for international peacebuilding turns to disappointment, if not cynicism. For many in the Balkans and other post-conflict environments, NGOs are not an aid to building a lasting peace but are part of the problem because of the turmoil they foster during their life cycles in a given country. The NGO Game will be useful to practitioners and policymakers interested in improving peacebuilding, the role of NGOs in peace and development, and the sustainability of local initiatives in post-conflict countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aNon-governmental organizationszFormer Yugoslav republics. 0aPeace-buildingxFormer Yugoslav republics. 0aPeace-buildingzFormer Yugoslav republics. 0aPostwar reconstructionxFormer Yugoslav republicsxYugoslavia. 0aPostwar reconstructionzFormer Yugoslav republics. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh  anongovernmental organization, NGO boom, international peacebuilding, Bosnia, Kosovo, post-Cold War, post-conflict countries, failure of the NGO boom, conflict, politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171273940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501712739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501712739/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles